Introduction¶

We have always been huge fans of soccer, especially Manchester United. In this project, we would like to take a look at the Premier League data and the teams in the last 12 seasons from 2006 to 2018 to gain some insight into the results through various measurements.

def generate_stats(team):
    season_list = df[(df.home_team == team) | (df.away_team == team)]['season'].unique()
    home_ptg = list()
    away_ptg = list()
    for season in season_list:
        home = df[(df.home_team == team) & (df.season == season)]
        away = df[(df.away_team == team) & (df.season == season)]
        home_ptg.append(sum(home.result == 'H')/len(home))
        away_ptg.append(sum(away.result == 'H')/len(away))
    stats = pd.DataFrame(list(zip(season_list, home_ptg,away_ptg)), columns = ['season','home_ptg','away_ptg'])
    stats
    tick = stats.index
    label = stats['season']
    width = 0.3 
    plt.figure(figsize = (12,5))
    plt.plot(label, stats['home_ptg'], color = 'blue',marker = 'o')
    plt.plot(label, stats['away_ptg'], color = 'red',marker = 'o')
    plt.xticks(tick, label, rotation = 90)
    plt.legend(['home','away'])
    plt.title(team)
    plt.ylabel('win percentage')
    plt.grid(linestyle ='-.',linewidth = 0.75)
    plt.show()

The line graphs below show the winning matches rate of each Premier League team between playing at home stadium vs. away stadium. Apparently, some top teams including Arsenal, Manchester United, or Chelsea are almost unbeatable at their home stadiums. However, a few lower-level teams actually have better results in some seasons when playing at their rivals' places, such as Newcastle United, West Ham United, or Aston Villa.

In order to have a deeper understanding of the data, we chose every top 10 in terms of average statistics for each factor and visualize them in different tables. Interestingly, Liverpool is the unluckiest team of the League so far as their balls hit the woodwork the most, whereas Manchester United has had the best defense class because of the highest clean sheets rate in many seasons.

In [10]:
for column in column_list:
    x = df2.groupby('team').mean().sort_values(column, ascending = True).tail(10)
    plt.figure(figsize = (12,5))
    plt.barh(x.index, x[column],color=['#6DFFE7','#651B40','#B83253','#FC666F','#FB8985','#FBA490','#F6BB93','#FFB900','#FFDE00','#55BEC0'])
    plt.title('Top 10'+ " " + column)
    plt.xlabel('Average # of' + " " + column)
    plt.show()

We also run the correlation between those factors to have a better understanding about their relationship.

In [12]:
team_list = df2.team.unique()
for team in team_list:
    x = df2[df2.team == team]
    plt.figure(figsize = (12,5))
    plt.plot(x.season, x.wins, color = 'red', marker = "o")
    plt.plot(x.season, x.losses, color = 'blue', marker = "o")
    plt.legend(['wins','losses'])
    plt.xticks(rotation = 45)
    plt.title(team)
    plt.grid(linestyle ='-.',linewidth = 0.75)
    plt.show()
In [14]:
pre_stats_united = df2[(df2.team == 'Manchester United')]

Since Manchester United has been through very tough times after the era of Sir Alex Ferguson, we decided to have a visualization to see how new coaches performed when they were in charge of the team. David Moyes was the chosen one right after Sir Alex's time. However, not only his winning rate was low, but also his loss rate was significantly higher than other seasons' data. On the other hand, Luis Van Gaal did a little better for two seasons, before Jose Mourinho was appointed in mid-2016. Overall, the "Special One" Mourinho was the best as he reached the highest winning rate during the 2017 - 2018 season with the lowest loss rate compared to the two others as well.
